# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: surface-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] The **contact angle** (symbol *θ*C) is the angle between a liquid surface and a solid surface where they meet.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] More specifically, it is the angle between the surface tangent on the liquid–vapor interface and the tangent on the solid–liquid interface at their intersection.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] It quantifies the *wettability* of a solid surface by a liquid via the Young equation.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] A given system of solid, liquid, and vapor at a given temperature and pressure has a unique equilibrium contact angle.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] However, in practice a dynamic phenomenon of contact angle hysteresis is often observed, ranging from the advancing (maximal) contact angle to the receding (minimal) contact angle.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] The equilibrium contact is within those values, and can be calculated from them.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] The equilibrium contact angle reflects the relative strength of the liquid, solid, and vapour molecular interaction.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] The contact angle depends upon the medium above the free surface of the liquid, and the nature of the liquid and solid in contact.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] It is independent of the inclination of solid to the liquid surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] It changes with surface tension and hence with the temperature and purity of the liquid.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] A recent molecular energetic perspective explains the classical 90° threshold by quantifying the ability of a system to compensate for hydrogen-bond defects it induces in its hydration layer.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] According to this approach, if the energetic compensation is less favorable than the defect cost in bulk water—estimated around −6 kJ/mol, known as the Defect Interaction Threshold (DIT)—the system exhibits hydrophobic behavior, consistent with contact angles exceeding 90°.
[src:surface-chemistry/contact-angle] This provides a non-arbitrary molecular basis for the macroscopic contact angle criterion and complements classical Young–Dupré interpretations.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The **Langmuir adsorption model** explains adsorption by assuming an adsorbate behaves as an ideal gas at isothermal conditions.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] According to the model, adsorption and desorption are reversible processes.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This model even explains the effect of pressure; *i.e.*, at these conditions the adsorbate's partial pressure $p_{A}$ is related to its volume V adsorbed onto a solid adsorbent.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The adsorbent, as indicated in the figure, is assumed to be an ideal solid surface composed of a series of distinct sites capable of binding the adsorbate.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The adsorbate binding is treated as a chemical reaction between the adsorbate gaseous molecule $A_{\text{g}}$ and an empty sorption site S.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] From these basic hypotheses the mathematical formulation of the Langmuir adsorption isotherm can be derived in various independent and complementary ways: by the kinetics, the thermodynamics, and the statistical mechanics approaches respectively (see below for the different demonstrations).
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] where $\theta _{A}$ is the fractional occupancy of the adsorption sites, i.e., the ratio of the volume V of gas adsorbed onto the solid to the volume $V_{\text{m}}$ of a gas molecules monolayer covering the whole surface of the solid and completely occupied by the adsorbate.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] A continuous monolayer of adsorbate molecules covering a homogeneous flat solid surface is the conceptual basis for this adsorption model.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] In 1916, Irving Langmuir presented his model for the adsorption of species onto simple surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Langmuir was awarded the Nobel Prize in 1932 for his work concerning surface chemistry.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] He hypothesized that a given surface has a certain number of equivalent sites to which a species can "stick", either by physisorption or chemisorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] His theory began when he postulated that gaseous molecules do not rebound elastically from a surface, but are held by it in a similar way to groups of molecules in solid bodies.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Langmuir published two papers that confirmed the assumption that adsorbed films do not exceed one molecule in thickness.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The first experiment involved observing electron emission from heated filaments in gases.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The second, a more direct evidence, examined and measured the films of liquid onto an adsorbent surface layer.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] He also noted that generally the attractive strength between the surface and the first layer of adsorbed substance is much greater than the strength between the first and second layer.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] However, there are instances where the subsequent layers may condense given the right combination of temperature and pressure.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Inherent within this model, the following assumptions are valid specifically for the simplest case: the adsorption of a single adsorbate onto a series of equivalent sites onto the surface of the solid.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The adsorbing gas adsorbs into an immobile state.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] All sites are energetically equivalent, and the energy of adsorption is equal for all sites.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Each site can hold at most one molecule (mono-layer coverage only).
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] No (or ideal) interactions between adsorbate molecules on adjacent sites.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] When the interactions are ideal, the energy of side-to-side interactions is equal for all sites regardless of the surface occupancy.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The mathematical expression of the Langmuir adsorption isotherm involving only one sorbing species can be demonstrated in different ways: the kinetics approach, the thermodynamics approach, and the statistical mechanics approach respectively.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] In case of two competing adsorbed species, the competitive adsorption model is required, while when a sorbed species dissociates into two distinct entities, the dissociative adsorption model need to be used.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This section provides a kinetic derivation for a single-adsorbate case.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The kinetic derivation applies to gas-phase adsorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The multiple-adsorbate case is covered in the competitive adsorption sub-section.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] At equilibrium, the rate of adsorption equals the rate of desorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] In condensed phases (solutions), adsorption to a solid surface is a competitive process between the solvent (*A*) and the solute (*B*) to occupy the binding site.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Solvent (bound) + Solute (free) ↔ Solvent (free) + Solute (bound).
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] For dilute solutions the activity of the solvent in bulk solution $a_{1}^{\text{b}}\simeq 1,$ and the activity coefficients ( $\gamma$ ) are also assumed to ideal on the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Note that the concentration of the solute adsorbate can be used instead of the activity coefficient.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] However, the equilibrium constant will no longer be dimensionless and will have units of reciprocal concentration instead.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The difference between the kinetic and thermodynamic derivations of the Langmuir model is that the thermodynamic uses activities as a starting point while the kinetic derivation uses rates of reaction.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The thermodynamic derivation allows for the activity coefficients of adsorbates in their bound and free states to be included.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The thermodynamic derivation is usually referred to as the "Langmuir-like equation".
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This derivation based on statistical mechanics was originally provided by Volmer and Mahnert in 1925.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] where $\zeta _{L}$ is the partition function of a single adsorbed molecule, $N_{S}$ is the number of adsorption sites (both occupied and unoccupied), and $N_{A}$ is the number of adsorbed molecules which should be less than or equal to $N_{S}$ .
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The terms in the bracket give the total partition function of the $N_{A}$ adsorbed molecules by taking a product of the individual partition functions (refer to Partition function of subsystems).
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The $1/N_{A}!$ factor accounts for the overcounting arising due to the indistinguishable nature of the adsorbates.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] $\mu _{A}$ is the chemical potential of an adsorbed molecule.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] q is the partition function of a single particle in the volume of V (only consider the translational freedom here).
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] We thus have $\mu _{g}=-k_{\rm {B}}T\ln(q/N)$ , where we use Stirling's approximation.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] It is plotted in the figure alongside demonstrating that the surface coverage increases quite rapidly with the partial pressure of the adsorbants, but levels off after *P* reaches *P*0.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The previous derivations assumed that there is only one species, *A*, adsorbing onto the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This section considers the case when there are two distinct adsorbates present in the system.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Consider two species *A* and *B* that compete for the same adsorption sites.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Each site can hold at most one molecule of *A,* or one molecule of *B*, but *not both simultaneously*.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] There are no interactions between adsorbate molecules on adjacent sites.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The other case of special importance is when a molecule *D*2 dissociates into two atoms upon adsorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The *D* atoms adsorb onto distinct sites on the surface of the solid and then move around and equilibrate.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Each site can hold at most one atom of *D*.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The 1/2 exponent on *p**D*2 arises because one gas phase molecule produces two adsorbed species.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The formation of Langmuir monolayers by adsorption onto a surface dramatically reduces the entropy of the molecular system.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] To find the entropy decrease, we find the entropy of the molecule when in the adsorbed condition.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] where $\lambda$ is the thermal de Broglie wavelength of the gas molecule.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The Langmuir adsorption model deviates significantly in many cases, primarily because it fails to account for the surface roughness of the adsorbent.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Rough inhomogeneous surfaces have multiple site types available for adsorption, with some parameters varying from site to site, such as the heat of adsorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Moreover, specific surface area is a scale-dependent quantity, and no single true value exists for this parameter.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Thus, the use of alternative probe molecules can often result in different obtained numerical values for surface area, rendering comparison problematic.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The model also ignores adsorbate–adsorbate interactions.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Experimentally, there is clear evidence for adsorbate–adsorbate interactions in heat of adsorption data.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] There are two kinds of adsorbate–adsorbate interactions: direct interaction and indirect interaction.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Direct interactions are between adjacent adsorbed molecules, which could make adsorbing near another adsorbate molecule more or less favorable and greatly affects high-coverage behavior.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] In indirect interactions, the adsorbate changes the surface around the adsorbed site, which in turn affects the adsorption of other adsorbate molecules nearby.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The modifications try to account for the points mentioned in above section like surface roughness, inhomogeneity, and adsorbate–adsorbate interactions.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Also known as the two-site Langmuir equation.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This equation describes the adsorption of one adsorbate to two or more distinct types of adsorption sites.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Each binding site can be described with its own Langmuir expression, as long as the adsorption at each binding site type is independent from the rest.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This equation works well for adsorption of some drug molecules to activated carbon in which some adsorbate molecules interact with hydrogen bonding while others interact with a different part of the surface by hydrophobic interactions (hydrophobic effect).
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The hydrophobic effect is independent of concentration, since $K_{2}a_{2}^{\text{b}}\gg 1.$ Therefore, the capacity of the adsorbent for hydrophobic interactions $q_{\text{HB}}$ can obtained from fitting to experimental data.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The entropy-driven adsorption originates from the restriction of translational motion of bulk water molecules by the adsorbate, which is alleviated upon adsorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The Freundlich isotherm is the most important multi-site adsorption isotherm for rough surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] where *α*F and *C*F are fitting parameters.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This equation implies that if one makes a log–log plot of adsorption data, the data will fit a straight line.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The Freundlich isotherm has two parameters, while Langmuir's equations has only one: as a result, it often fits the data on rough surfaces better than the Langmuir isotherm.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] However, the Freundlich equation is not unique; consequently, a good fit of the data points does not offer sufficient proof that the surface is heterogeneous.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] The heterogeneity of the surface can be confirmed with calorimetry.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Homogeneous surfaces (or heterogeneous surfaces that exhibit homogeneous adsorption (single-site)) have a constant $\Delta H$ of adsorption as a function of the occupied-sites fraction.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] On the other hand, heterogeneous adsorbents (multi-site) have a variable $\Delta H$ of adsorption depending on the sites occupation.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] When the adsorbate pressure (or concentration) is low, the fractional occupation is small and as a result, only low-energy sites are occupied, since these are the most stable.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] As the pressure increases, the higher-energy sites become occupied, resulting in a smaller $\Delta H$ of adsorption, given that adsorption is an exothermic process.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] A related equation is the *Toth equation*.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This isotherm takes into account indirect adsorbate–adsorbate interactions on adsorption isotherms.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Temkin noted experimentally that heats of adsorption would more often decrease than increase with increasing coverage.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] Brunauer, Emmett and Teller (BET) derived the first isotherm for multilayer adsorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] It assumes a random distribution of sites that are empty or that are covered with by one monolayer, two layers and so on, as illustrated alongside.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] in which [*A*]0 is the number of bare sites, and [*A*]i is the number of surface sites covered by *i* molecules.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This section describes the surface coverage when the adsorbate is in liquid phase and is a binary mixture.
[src:surface-chemistry/langmuir-adsorption-model] This equation describes competition of components "1" and "2".
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In surface science, **surface energy** (also **interfacial free energy** or **surface free energy**) quantifies the disruption of intermolecular bonds that occurs when a surface is created.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The surface energy may therefore be defined as the excess energy at the surface of a material compared to the bulk, or it is the work required to build an area of a particular surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Another way to view the surface energy is to relate it to the work required to cut a bulk sample, creating two surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] There is "excess energy" as a result of the now-incomplete, unrealized bonding between the two created surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Cutting a solid body into pieces disrupts its bonds and increases the surface area, and therefore increases surface energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] If the cutting is done reversibly, then conservation of energy means that the energy consumed by the cutting process will be equal to the energy inherent in the two new surfaces created.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The unit surface energy of a material would therefore be half of its energy of cohesion, all other things being equal; in practice, this is true only for a surface freshly prepared in vacuum.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Surfaces often change their form away from the simple "cleaved bond" model just implied above.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] They are found to be highly dynamic regions, which readily rearrange or react, so that energy is often reduced by such processes as passivation or adsorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The most common way to measure surface energy is through contact angle experiments.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In this method, the contact angle of the surface is measured with several liquids, usually water and diiodomethane.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Based on the contact angle results and knowing the surface tension of the liquids, the surface energy can be calculated.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In practice, this analysis is done automatically by a contact angle meter.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] There are several different models for calculating the surface energy based on the contact angle readings.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The most commonly used method is OWRK, which requires the use of two probe liquids and gives out as a result the total surface energy as well as divides it into polar and dispersive components.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Contact angle method is the standard surface energy measurement method due to its simplicity, applicability to a wide range of surfaces and quickness.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The measurement can be fully automated and is standardized.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In general, as surface energy increases, the contact angle decreases because more of the liquid is being "grabbed" by the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Conversely, as surface energy decreases, the contact angle increases, because the surface doesn't want to interact with the liquid.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The surface energy of a liquid may be measured by stretching a liquid membrane (which increases the surface area and hence the surface energy).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In that case, in order to increase the surface area of a mass of liquid by an amount, δA, a quantity of work, γ δA, is needed (where γ is the surface energy density of the liquid).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] However, such a method cannot be used to measure the surface energy of a solid because stretching of a solid membrane induces elastic energy in the bulk in addition to increasing the surface energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The surface energy of a solid is usually measured at high temperatures.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] At such temperatures the solid creeps and even though the surface area changes, the volume remains approximately constant.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The surface energy density of the solid can be computed by measuring P, r, and l at equilibrium.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This method is valid only if the solid is isotropic, meaning the surface energy is the same for all crystallographic orientations.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] While this is only strictly true for amorphous solids (glass) and liquids, isotropy is a good approximation for many other materials.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In particular, if the sample is polygranular (most metals) or made by powder sintering (most ceramics) this is a good approximation.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In the case of single-crystal materials, such as natural gemstones, anisotropy in the surface energy leads to faceting.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The shape of the crystal (assuming equilibrium growth conditions) is related to the surface energy by the Wulff construction.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The surface energy of the facets can thus be found to within a scaling constant by measuring the relative sizes of the facets.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Calculation of surface energy from first principles (for example, density functional theory) is an alternative approach to measurement.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Surface energy is estimated from the following variables: width of the d-band, the number of valence d-electrons, and the coordination number of atoms at the surface and in the bulk of the solid.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] is the total energy of surface slab obtained using density functional theory.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] is the number of atoms in the surface slab.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] For a slab, we have two surfaces and they are of the same type, which is reflected by the number 2 in the denominator.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] To guarantee this, we need to create the slab carefully to make sure that the upper and lower surfaces are of the same type.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Strength of adhesive contacts is determined by the work of adhesion which is also called *relative surface energy* of two contacting bodies.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The relative surface energy can be determined by detaching of bodies of well defined shape made of one material from the substrate made from the second material.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] For example, the relative surface energy of the interface "acrylic glass – gelatin" is equal to 0.03 N/m.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Experimental setup for measuring relative surface energy and its function can be seen in the video.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] To estimate the surface energy of a pure, uniform material, an individual region of the material can be modeled as a cube.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In order to move a cube from the bulk of a material to the surface, energy is required.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] where zσ and zβ are coordination numbers corresponding to the surface and the bulk regions of the material, and are equal to 5 and 6, respectively; *a*0 is the surface area of an individual molecule, and *W*AA is the pairwise intermolecular energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Here, M̄ corresponds to the molar mass of the molecule, ρ corresponds to the density, and *N*A is the Avogadro constant.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In order to determine the pairwise intermolecular energy, all intermolecular forces in the material must be broken.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This allows thorough investigation of the interactions that occur for single molecules.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] During sublimation of a substance, intermolecular forces between molecules are broken, resulting in a change in the material from solid to gas.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] For this reason, considering the enthalpy of sublimation can be useful in determining the pairwise intermolecular energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Using empirically tabulated values for enthalpy of sublimation, it is possible to determine the pairwise intermolecular energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Incorporating this value into the surface energy equation allows for the surface energy to be estimated.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The presence of an interface influences generally all thermodynamic parameters of a system.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] There are two models that are commonly used to demonstrate interfacial phenomena: the Gibbs ideal interface model and the Guggenheim model.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In order to demonstrate the thermodynamics of an interfacial system using the Gibbs model, the system can be divided into three parts: two immiscible liquids with volumes Vα and Vβ and an infinitesimally thin boundary layer known as the Gibbs dividing plane (σ) separating these two volumes.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] All extensive quantities of the system can be written as a sum of three components: bulk phase α, bulk phase β, and the interface σ.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Some examples include internal energy U, the number of molecules of the ith substance ni, and the entropy S.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] While these quantities can vary between each component, the sum within the system remains constant.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] At the interface, these values may deviate from those present within the bulk phases.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] where ciα and ciβ represent the concentration of substance i in bulk phase α and β, respectively.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Surface energy comes into play in wetting phenomena.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] To examine this, consider a drop of liquid on a solid substrate.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] If the surface energy of the substrate changes upon the addition of the drop, the substrate is said to be wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] where S is the spreading parameter, *γ*s the surface energy of the substrate, *γ*l the surface energy of the liquid, and *γ*s-l the interfacial energy between the substrate and the liquid.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] If *S* < 0, the liquid partially wets the substrate.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] If *S* > 0, the liquid completely wets the substrate.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] A way to experimentally determine wetting is to look at the contact angle (θ), which is the angle connecting the solid–liquid interface and the liquid–gas interface (as in the figure).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] , the liquid completely wets the substrate.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] , the liquid does not wet the substrate at all.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] where *γ*s-g is the interfacial energy between the solid and gas phases, *γ*s-l the interfacial energy between the substrate and the liquid, *γ*l-g is the interfacial energy between the liquid and gas phases, and θ is the contact angle between the solid–liquid and the liquid–gas interface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The energy of the bulk component of a solid substrate is determined by the types of interactions that hold the substrate together.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] High-energy substrates are held together by bonds, while low-energy substrates are held together by forces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Covalent, ionic, and metallic bonds are much stronger than forces such as van der Waals and hydrogen bonding.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] High-energy substrates are more easily wetted than low-energy substrates.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In addition, more complete wetting will occur if the substrate has a much higher surface energy than the liquid.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The most commonly used surface modification protocols are plasma activation, wet chemical treatment, including grafting, and thin-film coating.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Surface energy mimicking is a technique that enables merging the device manufacturing and surface modifications, including patterning, into a single processing step using a single device material.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Many techniques can be used to enhance wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Surface treatments, such as corona treatment, plasma treatment and acid etching, can be used to increase the surface energy of the substrate.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Additives can also be added to the liquid to decrease its surface tension.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This technique is employed often in paint formulations to ensure that they will be evenly spread on a surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] As a result of the surface tension inherent to liquids, curved surfaces are formed in order to minimize the area.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This phenomenon arises from the energetic cost of forming a surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] As such the Gibbs free energy of the system is minimized when the surface is curved.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The Kelvin equation is based on thermodynamic principles and is used to describe changes in vapor pressure caused by liquids with curved surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The cause for this change in vapor pressure is the Laplace pressure.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The vapor pressure of a drop is higher than that of a planar surface because the increased Laplace pressure causes the molecules to evaporate more easily.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Conversely, in liquids surrounding a bubble, the pressure with respect to the inner part of the bubble is reduced, thus making it more difficult for molecules to evaporate.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Pigments offer great potential in modifying the application properties of a coating.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Due to their fine particle size and inherently high surface energy, they often require a surface treatment in order to enhance their ease of dispersion in a liquid medium.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] A wide variety of surface treatments have been previously used, including the adsorption on the surface of a molecule in the presence of polar groups, monolayers of polymers, and layers of inorganic oxides on the surface of organic pigments.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] New surfaces are constantly being created as larger pigment particles get broken down into smaller subparticles.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] These newly-formed surfaces consequently contribute to larger surface energies, whereby the resulting particles often become cemented together into aggregates.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Because particles dispersed in liquid media are in constant thermal or Brownian motion, they exhibit a strong affinity for other pigment particles nearby as they move through the medium and collide.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This natural attraction is largely attributed to the powerful short-range van der Waals forces, as an effect of their surface energies.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] The chief purpose of pigment dispersion is to break down aggregates and form stable dispersions of optimally sized pigment particles.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This process generally involves three distinct stages: wetting, deaggregation, and stabilization.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] A surface that is easy to wet is desirable when formulating a coating that requires good adhesion and appearance.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This also minimizes the risks of surface tension related defects, such as crawling, cratering, and orange peel.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This is an essential requirement for pigment dispersions; for wetting to be effective, the surface tension of the pigment's vehicle must be lower than the surface free energy of the pigment.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This allows the vehicle to penetrate into the interstices of the pigment aggregates, thus ensuring complete wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Finally, the particles are subjected to a repulsive force in order to keep them separated from one another and lowers the likelihood of flocculation.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Dispersions may become stable through two different phenomena: charge repulsion and steric or entropic repulsion.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] In charge repulsion, particles that possess the same like electrostatic charges repel each other.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Alternatively, steric or entropic repulsion is a phenomenon used to describe the repelling effect when adsorbed layers of material (such as polymer molecules swollen with solvent) are present on the surface of the pigment particles in dispersion.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] Only certain portions (anchors) of the polymer molecules are adsorbed, with their corresponding loops and tails extending out into the solution.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] As the particles approach each other their adsorbed layers become crowded; this provides an effective steric barrier that prevents flocculation.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] This crowding effect is accompanied by a decrease in entropy, whereby the number of conformations possible for the polymer molecules is reduced in the adsorbed layer.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-energy] As a result, energy is increased and often gives rise to repulsive forces that aid in keeping the particles separated from each other.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] The field of surface chemistry started with a woman named Agnes Pockels, who pioneered the study of surface tension and created the Pockels slide trough, basis for the Langmuir-Blodgett trough despite being denied access to academic laboratories multiple times.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Around the same time, heterogeneous catalysis was pioneered by Paul Sabatier on hydrogenation and Fritz Haber on the Haber process.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Irving Langmuir was also one of the founders of this field, and the scientific journal on surface science, *Langmuir*, bears his name.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] The Langmuir adsorption equation is used to model monolayer adsorption where all surface adsorption sites have the same affinity for the adsorbing species and do not interact with each other.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Gerhard Ertl in 1974 described for the first time the adsorption of hydrogen on a palladium surface using a novel technique called LEED.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Similar studies with platinum, nickel, and iron followed.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Most recent developments in surface sciences include the 2007 Nobel prize of Chemistry winner Gerhard Ertl's advancements in surface chemistry, specifically his investigation of the interaction between carbon monoxide molecules and platinum surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Surface chemistry can be roughly defined as the study of chemical reactions at interfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] It is closely related to surface engineering, which aims at modifying the chemical composition of a surface by incorporation of selected elements or functional groups that produce various desired effects or improvements in the properties of the surface or interface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Surface science is of particular importance to the fields of heterogeneous catalysis, electrochemistry, and geochemistry.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] The adhesion of gas or liquid molecules to the surface is known as adsorption.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] This can be due to either chemisorption or physisorption, and the strength of molecular adsorption to a catalyst surface is critically important to the catalyst's performance (see Sabatier principle).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] However, it is difficult to study these phenomena in real catalyst particles, which have complex structures.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Instead, well-defined single crystal surfaces of catalytically active materials such as platinum are often used as model catalysts.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Multi-component materials systems are used to study interactions between catalytically active metal particles and supporting oxides; these are produced by growing ultra-thin films or particles on a single crystal surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Results can be fed into chemical models or used toward the rational design of new catalysts.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Reaction mechanisms can also be clarified due to the atomic-scale precision of surface science measurements.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Electrochemistry is the study of processes driven through an applied potential at a solid–liquid or liquid–liquid interface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] The behavior of an electrode–electrolyte interface is affected by the distribution of ions in the liquid phase next to the interface forming the electrical double layer.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Adsorption and desorption events can be studied at atomically flat single-crystal surfaces as a function of applied potential, time and solution conditions using spectroscopy, scanning probe microscopy and surface X-ray scattering.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] These studies link traditional electrochemical techniques such as cyclic voltammetry to direct observations of interfacial processes.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Geological phenomena such as iron cycling and soil contamination are controlled by the interfaces between minerals and their environment.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] The atomic-scale structure and chemical properties of mineral–solution interfaces are studied using *in situ* synchrotron X-ray techniques such as X-ray reflectivity, X-ray standing waves, and X-ray absorption spectroscopy as well as scanning probe microscopy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] For example, studies of heavy metal or actinide adsorption onto mineral surfaces reveal molecular-scale details of adsorption, enabling more accurate predictions of how these contaminants travel through soils or disrupt natural dissolution–precipitation cycles.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Surface physics can be roughly defined as the study of physical interactions that occur at interfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Some of the topics investigated in surface physics include friction, surface states, surface diffusion, surface reconstruction, surface phonons and plasmons, epitaxy, the emission and tunneling of electrons, spintronics, and the self-assembly of nanostructures on surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Techniques to investigate processes at surfaces include surface X-ray scattering, scanning probe microscopy, surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] The study and analysis of surfaces involves both physical and chemical analysis techniques.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Several modern methods probe the topmost 1–10 nm of surfaces exposed to vacuum.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Many of these techniques require vacuum as they rely on the detection of electrons or ions emitted from the surface under study.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Moreover, in general ultra-high vacuum, in the range of 10−7 pascal pressure or better, it is necessary to reduce surface contamination by residual gas, by reducing the number of molecules reaching the sample over a given time period.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] At 0.1 mPa (10−6 torr) partial pressure of a contaminant and standard temperature, it only takes on the order of 1 second to cover a surface with a one-to-one monolayer of contaminant to surface atoms, so much lower pressures are needed for measurements.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] This is found by an order of magnitude estimate for the (number) specific surface area of materials and the impingement rate formula from the kinetic theory of gases.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Purely optical techniques can be used to study interfaces under a wide variety of conditions.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Reflection-absorption infrared, dual polarisation interferometry, surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy and sum frequency generation spectroscopy can be used to probe solid–vacuum as well as solid–gas, solid–liquid, and liquid–gas surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Multi-parametric surface plasmon resonance works in solid–gas, solid–liquid, liquid–gas surfaces and can detect even sub-nanometer layers.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] It probes the interaction kinetics as well as dynamic structural changes such as liposome collapse or swelling of layers in different pH.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Dual-polarization interferometry is used to quantify the order and disruption in birefringent thin films.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] This has been used, for example, to study the formation of lipid bilayers and their interaction with membrane proteins.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Acoustic techniques, such as quartz crystal microbalance with dissipation monitoring, is used for time-resolved measurements of solid–vacuum, solid–gas and solid–liquid interfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] The method allows for analysis of molecule–surface interactions as well as structural changes and viscoelastic properties of the adlayer.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] X-ray scattering and spectroscopy techniques are also used to characterize surfaces and interfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] While some of these measurements can be performed using laboratory X-ray sources, many require the high intensity and energy tunability of synchrotron radiation.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] X-ray crystal truncation rods (CTR) and X-ray standing wave (XSW) measurements probe changes in surface and adsorbate structures with sub-Ångström resolution.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Surface-extended X-ray absorption fine structure (SEXAFS) measurements reveal the coordination structure and chemical state of adsorbates.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Grazing-incidence small angle X-ray scattering (GISAXS) yields the size, shape, and orientation of nanoparticles on surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] The crystal structure and texture of thin films can be investigated using grazing-incidence X-ray diffraction (GIXD, GIXRD).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) is a standard tool for measuring the chemical states of surface species and for detecting the presence of surface contamination.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Surface sensitivity is achieved by detecting photoelectrons with kinetic energies of about 10–1000 eV, which have corresponding inelastic mean free paths of only a few nanometers.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] This technique has been extended to operate at near-ambient pressures (ambient pressure XPS, AP-XPS) to probe more realistic gas–solid and liquid–solid interfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Performing XPS with hard X-rays at synchrotron light sources yields photoelectrons with kinetic energies of several keV (hard X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy, HAXPES), enabling access to chemical information from buried interfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] Modern physical analysis methods include scanning-tunneling microscopy (STM) and a family of methods descended from it, including atomic force microscopy (AFM).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] These microscopies have considerably increased the ability of surface scientists to measure the physical structure of many surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-science] For example, they make it possible to follow reactions at the solid–gas interface in real space, if those proceed on a time scale accessible by the instrument.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] An example of its relevance is the tendency of liquid surfaces at rest to shrink to the minimum surface area possible.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Because of the relatively high attraction of water molecules to each other through a web of hydrogen bonds, water has a higher surface tension (72.8 millinewtons (mN) per meter at 20 °C) than most other liquids.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This allows objects with a higher density than water such as razor blades and insects (e.g. water striders) to float on a water surface without becoming even partly submerged.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The magnitude of the surface tension is connected to the forces between the molecules at the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Therefore surfactants are often used to reduce it so there is more contact between the liquid and another material, for instance detergents.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] It can also lead to pressure inside water bubbles, as well as many other phenomena; it is a classic, well-studied property common to all liquids.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Due to the cohesive forces, a molecule located away from the surface is pulled equally in every direction by neighboring liquid molecules, resulting in a net force of zero.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The molecules at the surface do not have an equal number of molecules on all sides of them and therefore are pulled inward.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This creates some internal pressure and forces liquid surfaces to contract to the minimum area.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] There is also a tension parallel to the surface at the liquid-air interface which will resist an external force, due to the cohesive forces between the molecules.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The forces of attraction acting between molecules of the same type are called cohesive forces, while those acting between molecules of different types are called adhesive forces.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The balance between the cohesion of the liquid and its adhesion to the material of the container determines the degree of wetting, the contact angle, and the shape of the meniscus.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] When cohesion dominates (specifically, adhesion energy is less than half of cohesion energy) the wetting is low and the meniscus is convex at a vertical wall (as for mercury in a glass container).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] On the other hand, when adhesion dominates (when adhesion energy is more than half of cohesion energy) the wetting is high and the similar meniscus is concave (as in water in a glass).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Surface tension is responsible for the shape of liquid droplets.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Although easily deformed, droplets of water tend to be pulled into a spherical shape by the imbalance in cohesive forces of the surface layer.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In the absence of other forces, drops of virtually all liquids would be approximately spherical.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The spherical shape minimizes the necessary "wall tension" of the surface layer according to Laplace's law.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Another way to view surface tension is in terms of energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] A molecule in contact with a neighbor is in a lower state of energy than if it were alone.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The interior molecules have as many neighbors as they can possibly have, but the boundary molecules are missing neighbors (compared to interior molecules) and therefore have higher energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For the liquid to minimize its energy state, the number of higher energy boundary molecules must be minimized.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The minimized number of boundary molecules results in a minimal surface area.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] As a result of surface area minimization, a surface will assume a smooth shape.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Surface tension, represented by the symbol *γ* (alternatively *σ* or *T*), is measured in force per unit length.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Its SI unit is newton per metre but the cgs unit of dyne per centimetre is also used, particularly in the older literature.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Surface tension can be defined in terms of force or energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Surface tension γ of a liquid is the force per unit length.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In the illustration on the right, the rectangular frame, composed of three unmovable sides (black) that form a "U" shape, and a fourth movable side (blue) that can slide to the right.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Surface tension will pull the blue bar to the left; the force F required to hold the movable side is proportional to the length L of the mobile side.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Thus the ratio ⁠*F*/*L*⁠ depends only on the intrinsic properties of the liquid (composition, temperature, etc.), not on its geometry.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For example, if the frame had a more complicated shape, the ratio ⁠*F*/*L*⁠, with L the length of the movable side and F the force required to stop it from sliding, is found to be the same for all shapes.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] We therefore define the surface tension as $\gamma ={\frac {F}{2L}}.$ The reason for the ⁠1/2⁠ is that the film has two sides (two surfaces), each of which contributes equally to the force; so the force contributed by a single side is *γL* = ⁠*F*/2⁠.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Surface tension γ of a liquid is the ratio of the change in the energy of the liquid to the change in the surface area of the liquid (that led to the change in energy).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This can be easily related to the previous definition in terms of force: if F is the force required to stop the side from *starting* to slide, then this is also the force that would keep the side in the state of *sliding at a constant speed* (by Newton's second law).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] But if the side is moving to the right (in the direction the force is applied), then the surface area of the stretched liquid is increasing while the applied force is doing work on the liquid.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This means that increasing the surface area increases the energy of the film.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The work done by the force F in moving the side by distance Δ*x* is *W* = *F*Δ*x*; at the same time the total area of the film increases by Δ*A* = 2*L*Δ*x* (the factor of 2 is here because the liquid has two sides, two surfaces).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Thus, multiplying both the numerator and the denominator of *γ* = ⁠1/2⁠⁠*F*/*L*⁠ by Δ*x*, we get $\gamma ={\frac {F}{2L}}={\frac {F\Delta x}{2L\Delta x}}={\frac {W}{\Delta A}}.$ This work W is, by the usual arguments, interpreted as being stored as potential energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Consequently, surface tension can be also measured in SI system as joules per square meter and in the cgs system as ergs per cm2.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Since mechanical systems try to find a state of minimum potential energy, a free droplet of liquid naturally assumes a spherical shape, which has the minimum surface area for a given volume as first pointed out by Gibbs.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The equivalence of measurement of energy per unit area to force per unit length can be proven by dimensional analysis.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Formation of drops occurs when a mass of liquid is stretched.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For example, water can adhere to a faucet gaining mass until it is stretched to a point where the surface tension can no longer keep the drop linked to the faucet.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] It then separates and surface tension forms the drop into a sphere.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] If a stream of water were running from the faucet, the stream would break up into drops during its fall.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Gravity stretches the stream, then surface tension pinches it into spheres.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Flotation of objects denser than water occurs when the object is nonwettable and its weight is small enough to be borne by the forces arising from surface tension.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For example, water striders use surface tension to walk on the surface of a pond in the following way.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The nonwettability of the water strider's leg means there is no attraction between molecules of the leg and molecules of the water, so when the leg pushes down on the water, the surface tension of the water only tries to recover its flatness from its deformation due to the leg.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This behavior of the water pushes the water strider upward so it can stand on the surface of the water as long as its mass is small enough that the water can support it.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The surface of the water behaves like an elastic film: the insect's feet cause indentations in the water's surface, increasing its surface area and tendency of minimization of surface curvature (so area) of the water pushes the insect's feet upward.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Separation of oil and water (such as water and liquid wax in a lava lamp) is caused by a tension in the surface between dissimilar liquids.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This type of surface tension is called "interface tension", but its chemistry is the same.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Tears of wine is the formation of drops and rivulets on the side of a glass containing an alcoholic beverage.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Its cause is a complex interaction between the differing surface tensions of water and ethanol; it is induced by a combination of surface tension modification of water by ethanol together with ethanol evaporating faster than water.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] If no force acts normal to a tensioned surface, the surface must remain flat.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] But if the pressure on one side of the surface differs from pressure on the other side, the pressure difference times surface area results in a normal force.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In order for the surface tension forces to cancel the force due to pressure, the surface must be curved.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The diagram shows how surface curvature of a tiny patch of surface leads to a net component of surface tension forces acting normal to the center of the patch.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The quantity in parentheses on the right hand side is in fact (twice) the mean curvature of the surface (depending on normalisation).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Solutions to this equation determine the shape of water drops, puddles, menisci, soap bubbles, and all other shapes determined by surface tension (such as the shape of the impressions that a water strider's feet make on the surface of a pond).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The table below shows how the internal pressure of a water droplet increases with decreasing radius.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For not very small drops the effect is subtle, but the pressure difference becomes enormous when the drop sizes approach the molecular size.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] When an object is placed on a liquid, its weight *F*w depresses the surface, and if surface tension and downward force become equal then it is balanced by the surface tension forces on either side *F*s, which are each parallel to the water's surface at the points where it contacts the object.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Notice that small movement in the body may cause the object to sink.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] As the angle of contact decreases, surface tension decreases.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The horizontal components of the two *F*s arrows point in opposite directions, so they cancel each other, but the vertical components point in the same direction and therefore add up to balance *F*w.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The object's surface must not be wettable for this to happen, and its weight must be low enough for the surface tension to support it.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] To find the shape of the minimal surface bounded by some arbitrary shaped frame using strictly mathematical means can be a daunting task.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Yet by fashioning the frame out of wire and dipping it in soap-solution, a locally minimal surface will appear in the resulting soap-film within seconds.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The reason for this is that the pressure difference across a fluid interface is proportional to the mean curvature, as seen in the Young–Laplace equation.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For an open soap film, the pressure difference is zero, hence the mean curvature is zero, and minimal surfaces have the property of zero mean curvature.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The surface of any liquid is an interface between that liquid and some other medium.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The top surface of a pond, for example, is an interface between the pond water and the air.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Surface tension, then, is not a property of the liquid alone, but a property of the liquid's interface with another medium.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] If a liquid is in a container, then besides the liquid/air interface at its top surface, there is also an interface between the liquid and the walls of the container.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The surface tension between the liquid and air is usually different (greater) than its surface tension with the walls of a container.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] And where the two surfaces meet, their geometry must be such that all forces balance.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Where the two surfaces meet, they form a contact angle, θ, which is the angle the tangent to the surface makes with the solid surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Note that the angle is measured *through the liquid*, as shown in the diagrams above.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The diagram to the right shows two examples.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Tension forces are shown for the liquid–air interface, the liquid–solid interface, and the solid–air interface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In the diagram, both the vertical and horizontal forces must cancel exactly at the contact point, known as equilibrium.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The horizontal component of *f*la is canceled by the adhesive force, *f*A.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The more telling balance of forces, though, is in the vertical direction.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The vertical component of *f*la must exactly cancel the difference of the forces along the solid surface, *f*ls − *f*sa.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This same relationship exists in the diagram on the right.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Observe that in the special case of a water–silver interface where the contact angle is equal to 90°, the liquid–solid/solid–air surface tension difference is exactly zero.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Another special case is where the contact angle is exactly 180°.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Water with specially prepared Teflon approaches this.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Contact angle of 180° occurs when the liquid–solid surface tension is exactly equal to the liquid–air surface tension.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] An old style mercury barometer consists of a vertical glass tube about 1 cm in diameter partially filled with mercury, and with a vacuum (called Torricelli's vacuum) in the unfilled volume (see diagram to the right).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Notice that the mercury level at the center of the tube is higher than at the edges, making the upper surface of the mercury dome-shaped.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The center of mass of the entire column of mercury would be slightly lower if the top surface of the mercury were flat over the entire cross-section of the tube.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] But the dome-shaped top gives slightly less surface area to the entire mass of mercury.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Again the two effects combine to minimize the total potential energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Such a surface shape is known as a convex meniscus.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] We consider the surface area of the entire mass of mercury, including the part of the surface that is in contact with the glass, because mercury does not adhere to glass at all.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] So the surface tension of the mercury acts over its entire surface area, including where it is in contact with the glass.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] If instead of glass, the tube was made out of copper, the situation would be very different.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] So in a copper tube, the level of mercury at the center of the tube will be lower than at the edges (that is, it would be a concave meniscus).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In a situation where the liquid adheres to the walls of its container, we consider the part of the fluid's surface area that is in contact with the container to have *negative* surface tension.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The fluid then works to maximize the contact surface area.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] So in this case increasing the area in contact with the container decreases rather than increases the potential energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] That decrease is enough to compensate for the increased potential energy associated with lifting the fluid near the walls of the container.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] If a tube is sufficiently narrow and the liquid adhesion to its walls is sufficiently strong, surface tension can draw liquid up the tube in a phenomenon known as capillary action.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Pouring mercury onto a horizontal flat sheet of glass results in a puddle that has a perceptible thickness.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The puddle will spread out only to the point where it is a little under half a centimetre thick, and no thinner.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Again this is due to the action of mercury's strong surface tension.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The liquid mass flattens out because that brings as much of the mercury to as low a level as possible, but the surface tension, at the same time, is acting to reduce the total surface area.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The result of the compromise is a puddle of a nearly fixed thickness.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The same surface tension demonstration can be done with water, lime water or even saline, but only on a surface made of a substance to which water does not adhere.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Water poured onto a smooth, flat, horizontal wax surface, say a waxed sheet of glass, will behave similarly to the mercury poured onto glass.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In reality, the thicknesses of the puddles will be slightly less than what is predicted by the above formula because very few surfaces have a contact angle of 180° with any liquid.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The formula also predicts that when the contact angle is 0°, the liquid will spread out into a micro-thin layer over the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Such a surface is said to be fully wettable by the liquid.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In day-to-day life all of us observe that a stream of water emerging from a faucet will break up into droplets, no matter how smoothly the stream is emitted from the faucet.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This is due to a phenomenon called the Plateau–Rayleigh instability, which is entirely a consequence of the effects of surface tension.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The explanation of this instability begins with the existence of tiny perturbations in the stream.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] These are always present, no matter how smooth the stream is.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] If the perturbations are resolved into sinusoidal components, we find that some components grow with time while others decay with time.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Among those that grow with time, some grow at faster rates than others.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Whether a component decays or grows, and how fast it grows is entirely a function of its wave number (a measure of how many peaks and troughs per centimeter) and the radii of the original cylindrical stream.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Gibbs developed the thermodynamic theory of capillarity based on the idea of surfaces of discontinuity.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Gibbs considered the case of a sharp mathematical surface being placed somewhere within the microscopically fuzzy physical interface that exists between two homogeneous substances.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Realizing that the exact choice of the surface's location was somewhat arbitrary, he left it flexible.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Considering a given subvolume V containing a surface of discontinuity, the volume is divided by the mathematical surface into two parts A and B, with volumes $V_{\text{A}}$ and $V_{\text{B}}$ , with $V=V_{\text{A}}+V_{\text{B}}$ exactly.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For sufficiently macroscopic and gently curved surfaces, the surface free energy must simply be proportional to the surface area: $\Omega _{\text{S}}=\gamma A,$ for surface tension $\gamma$ and surface area A .
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] As stated above, this implies the mechanical work needed to increase a surface area *A* is *dW* = *γ dA*, assuming the volumes on each side do not change.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] From this it is easy to understand why decreasing the surface area of a mass of liquid is always spontaneous, provided it is not coupled to any other energy changes.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] It follows that in order to increase surface area, a certain amount of energy must be added.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Gibbs and other scientists have wrestled with the arbitrariness in the exact microscopic placement of the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For microscopic surfaces with very tight curvatures, it is not correct to assume the surface tension is independent of size, and topics like the Tolman length come into play.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Gibbs emphasized that for solids, the surface free energy may be completely different from surface stress (what he called surface tension): the surface free energy is the work required to *form* the surface, while surface stress is the work required to *stretch* the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In the case of a two-fluid interface, there is no distinction between forming and stretching because the fluids and the surface completely replenish their nature when the surface is stretched.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For a solid, stretching the surface, even elastically, results in a fundamentally changed surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Further, the surface stress on a solid is a directional quantity (a stress tensor) while surface energy is scalar.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Fifteen years after Gibbs, J.D. van der Waals developed the theory of capillarity effects based on the hypothesis of a continuous variation of density.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] He added to the energy density the term $c(\nabla \rho )^{2},$ where *c* is the capillarity coefficient and *ρ* is the density.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For the multiphase *equilibria*, the results of the van der Waals approach practically coincide with the Gibbs formulae, but for modelling of the *dynamics* of phase transitions the van der Waals approach is much more convenient.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The van der Waals capillarity energy is now widely used in the phase field models of multiphase flows.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Such terms are also discovered in the dynamics of non-equilibrium gases.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The pressure inside an ideal spherical bubble can be derived from thermodynamic free energy considerations.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The above free energy can be written as: $\Omega =-\Delta PV_{\text{A}}-p_{\text{B}}V+\gamma A$ where $\Delta P=p_{\text{A}}-p_{\text{B}}$ is the pressure difference between the inside (A) and outside (B) of the bubble, and $V_{\text{A}}$ is the bubble volume.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Substituting these relations into the previous expression, we find $\Delta P={\frac {2}{R}}\gamma ,$ which is equivalent to the Young–Laplace equation when *Rx* = *Ry*.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Surface tension is dependent on temperature.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For that reason, when a value is given for the surface tension of an interface, temperature must be explicitly stated.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The general trend is that surface tension decreases with the increase of temperature, reaching a value of 0 at the critical temperature.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Both Guggenheim–Katayama and Eötvös take into account the fact that surface tension reaches 0 at the critical temperature, whereas Ramay and Shields fails to match reality at this endpoint.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] What complicates the effect is that a solute can exist in a different concentration at the surface of a solvent than in its bulk.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This difference varies from one solute–solvent combination to another.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Certain assumptions are taken in its deduction, therefore Gibbs isotherm can only be applied to ideal (very dilute) solutions with two components.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The Clausius–Clapeyron relation leads to another equation also attributed to Kelvin, as the Kelvin equation.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] It explains why, because of surface tension, the vapor pressure for small droplets of liquid in suspension is greater than standard vapor pressure of that same liquid when the interface is flat.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] That is to say that when a liquid is forming small droplets, the equilibrium concentration of its vapor in its surroundings is greater.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This arises because the pressure inside the droplet is greater than outside.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The effect explains supersaturation of vapors.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] In the absence of nucleation sites, tiny droplets must form before they can evolve into larger droplets.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This requires a vapor pressure many times the vapor pressure at the phase transition point.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This equation is also used in catalyst chemistry to assess mesoporosity for solids.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The effect can be viewed in terms of the average number of molecular neighbors of surface molecules (see diagram).
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The effect becomes clear for very small drop sizes, as a drop of 1 nm radius has about 100 molecules inside, which is a quantity small enough to require a quantum mechanics analysis.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Because surface tension manifests itself in various effects, it offers a number of paths to its measurement.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Which method is optimal depends upon the nature of the liquid being measured, the conditions under which its tension is to be measured, and the stability of its surface when it is deformed.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] An instrument that measures surface tension is called tensiometer.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] where both T and the critical temperature *T*C = 647.096 K are expressed in kelvins.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The region of validity the entire vapor–liquid saturation curve, from the triple point (0.01 °C) to the critical point.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] It also provides reasonable results when extrapolated to metastable (supercooled) conditions, down to at least −25 °C.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] This formulation was originally adopted by IAPWS in 1976 and was adjusted in 1994 to conform to the International Temperature Scale of 1990.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The uncertainty of this formulation is given over the full range of temperature by IAPWS.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] For temperatures below 100 °C, the uncertainty is ±0.5%.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] Nayar et al. published reference data for the surface tension of seawater over the salinity range of 20 ≤ S ≤ 131 g/kg and a temperature range of 1 ≤ t ≤ 92 °C at atmospheric pressure.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The range of temperature and salinity encompasses both the oceanographic range and the range of conditions encountered in thermal desalination technologies.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The uncertainty of the measurements varied from 0.18 to 0.37 mN/m with the average uncertainty being 0.22 mN/m.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The average absolute percentage deviation between measurements and the correlation was 0.19% while the maximum deviation is 0.60%.
[src:surface-chemistry/surface-tension] The International Association for the Properties of Water and Steam (IAPWS) has adopted this correlation as an international standard guideline.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The degree of wetting, or *wettability*, is dependent on the force balance between adhesive and cohesive forces, occurring when liquid and solid make contact in the presence of another physical phase.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] As such, wetting is of importance to bonding and adherence of substances in different phases.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The wetting *power* of a liquid, and surface forces contributing to its wettability, are also responsible for capillary action.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Surfactants can be used to increase the wetting power of liquids (i.e., water) by reducing surface forces.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] There are two types of wetting: *non-reactive* and *reactive* wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Wetting has gained increased attention in nanotechnology and nanoscience research following the development of nanomaterials, such as graphene, carbon nanotubes, and boron nitride nanomesh.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Wetting of a solid material with a liquid substance occurs when adhesive forces allow the liquid (as a droplet) to spread across the surface of the solid at the *solid-liquid* interface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] However, cohesive forces acting on the liquid – at the *liquid–vapor interface* – counteract the adhesive forces to prevent the droplet from making full contact with the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The contact angle (*θ*), as seen in Figure 1, is the angle at which the liquid–vapor interface meets the solid–liquid interface, and is determined by the balance between adhesive and cohesive forces.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] As the tendency of a drop to spread out over a flat, solid surface increases, the contact angle decreases.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Thus, the contact angle is used as an inverse measure of wettability.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A contact angle less than 90° (low contact angle) usually indicates that wetting of the surface is very favorable, and the fluid will spread over a large area of the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Contact angles greater than 90° (high contact angle) generally mean that wetting of the surface is unfavorable, so the fluid will minimize contact with the surface and form a compact liquid droplet.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] For water, a wettable surface may also be termed hydrophilic and a nonwettable surface hydrophobic.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Superhydrophobic surfaces have contact angles greater than 150°, showing almost no contact between the liquid drop and the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This is sometimes referred to as the "Lotus effect".
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The table describes varying contact angles and their corresponding solid/liquid and liquid/liquid interactions.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] For nonwater liquids, the term lyophilic is used for low contact angle conditions and lyophobic is used when higher contact angles result.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Similarly, the terms omniphobic and omniphilic apply to both polar and apolar liquids.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Recent studies have introduced a quantitative molecular definition of hydrophobicity and wetting transitions, based on the energetic cost required to stabilize hydrogen-bond defects in the hydration shell of a surface or solute.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] According to this approach, a system is considered hydrophobic if it fails to compensate the energetic penalty of missing hydrogen bonds with an energy at least as favorable as the defect cost in bulk water, estimated around −6 kJ/mol (approximately 30% of a typical hydrogen bond energy).
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This criterion, known as the Defect Interaction Threshold (DIT), aligns remarkably with the classical 90° contact angle threshold, thus providing a non-arbitrary molecular basis for the onset of hydrophobic behavior.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Liquids can interact with two main types of solid surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Traditionally, solid surfaces have been divided into high-energy and low-energy solids.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The relative energy of a solid has to do with the bulk nature of the solid itself.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Solids such as metals, glasses, and ceramics are known as 'hard solids' because the chemical bonds that hold them together (e.g., covalent, ionic, or metallic) are very strong.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Thus, it takes a large amount of energy to break these solids (alternatively, a large amount of energy is required to cut the bulk and make two separate surfaces), so they are termed "high-energy".
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Most molecular liquids achieve complete wetting with high-energy surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The other type of solid is weak molecular crystals (e.g., fluorocarbons, hydrocarbons, etc.) where the molecules are held together essentially by physical forces (e.g., van der Waals forces and hydrogen bonds).
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Since these solids are held together by weak forces, a very low amount of energy is required to break them, thus they are termed "low-energy".
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Depending on the type of liquid chosen, low-energy surfaces can permit either complete or partial wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Dynamic surfaces have been reported that undergo changes in surface energy upon the application of an appropriate stimuli.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] For example, a surface presenting photon-driven molecular motors was shown to undergo changes in water contact angle when switched between bistable conformations of differing surface energies.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Low-energy surfaces primarily interact with liquids through dispersive (van der Waals) forces.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Zisman observed that cos *θ* increases linearly as the surface tension (*γ*LV) of the liquid decreased.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Thus, he was able to establish a linear function between cos *θ* and the surface tension (*γ*LV) for various organic liquids.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A surface is more wettable when *γ*LV and *θ* is low.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Zisman termed the intercept of these lines when cos *θ* = 1 as the critical surface tension (*γ*c) of that surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This critical surface tension is an important parameter because it is a characteristic of only the solid.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Knowing the critical surface tension of a solid, it is possible to predict the wettability of the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The wettability of a surface is determined by the outermost chemical groups of the solid.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Differences in wettability between surfaces that are similar in structure are due to differences in the packing of the atoms.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] For instance, if a surface has branched chains, it will have poorer packing than a surface with straight chains.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Lower critical surface tension means a less wettable material surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] An ideal surface is flat, rigid, perfectly smooth, chemically homogeneous, and has zero contact angle hysteresis.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Zero hysteresis implies the advancing and receding contact angles are equal.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In other words, only one thermodynamically stable contact angle exists.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When a drop of liquid is placed on such a surface, the characteristic contact angle is formed as depicted in Figure 1.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Furthermore, on an ideal surface, the drop will return to its original shape if it is disturbed.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The following derivations apply only to ideal solid surfaces; they are only valid for the state in which the interfaces are not moving and the phase boundary line exists in equilibrium.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Figure 3 shows the line of contact where three phases meet.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In equilibrium, the net force per unit length acting along the boundary line between the three phases must be zero.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] where *α*, *β*, and *θ* are the angles shown and γij is the surface energy between the two indicated phases.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] These relations can also be expressed by an analog to a triangle known as Neumann's triangle, shown in Figure 4.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Neumann's triangle is consistent with the geometrical restriction that $\alpha +\beta +\theta =2\pi$ , and applying the law of sines and law of cosines to it produce relations that describe how the interfacial angles depend on the ratios of surface energies.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Because these three surface energies form the sides of a triangle, they are constrained by the triangle inequalities, *γ**ij* < *γ**jk* + *γ**ik*, meaning that not one of the surface tensions can exceed the sum of the other two.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] If three fluids with surface energies that do not follow these inequalities are brought into contact, no equilibrium configuration consistent with Figure 3 will exist.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] which relates the surface tensions between the three phases: solid, liquid and gas.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Subsequently, this predicts the contact angle of a liquid droplet on a solid surface from knowledge of the three surface energies involved.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This equation also applies if the "gas" phase is another liquid, immiscible with the droplet of the first "liquid" phase.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Consider the interface as a curve $y(x)$ for $x\in I=[0,L]$ where L is a free parameter.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] with the constraints $y(0)=y(L)=0$ , which we can write as $\int _{I}y'dx=0$ and fixed volume $\int _{I}ydx=A$ .
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] where $\lambda _{i}$ are Lagrange multipliers.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Now, we recall that the boundary is free in the x direction and L is a free parameter.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The Young equation assumes a perfectly flat and rigid surface often referred to as an ideal surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In many cases, surfaces are far from this ideal situation, and two are considered here: the case of rough surfaces and the case of smooth surfaces that are still real (finitely rigid).
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Even in a perfectly smooth surface, a drop will assume a wide spectrum of contact angles ranging from the so-called advancing contact angle, $\theta _{\mathrm {A} }$ , to the so-called receding contact angle, $\theta _{\mathrm {R} }$ .
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The Young–Dupré equation (Thomas Young 1805; Anthanase Dupré and Paul Dupré 1869) dictates that neither *γ*SG nor *γ*SL can be larger than the sum of the other two surface energies.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The consequence of this restriction is the prediction of complete wetting when *γ*SG > *γ*SL + *γ*LG and zero wetting when *γ*SL > *γ*SG + *γ*LG.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The lack of a solution to the Young–Dupré equation is an indicator that there is no equilibrium configuration with a contact angle between 0 and 180° for those situations.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When *S* > 0, the liquid wets the surface completely (complete wetting).
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] which only has physical solutions for *θ* when *S* < 0.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] With improvements in measuring techniques such as AFM, confocal microscopy and SEM, researchers were able to produce and image droplets at ever smaller scales.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] With the reduction in droplet size came new experimental observations of wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] These observations confirm that the modified Young's equation does not hold at the micro-nano scales.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In addition the sign of the line tension is not maintained through the modified Young's equation.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Usually, the *VdP* term has been neglected for large droplets, however, *VdP* work becomes significant at small scales.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The variation in pressure at constant volume at the free liquid-vapor boundary is due to the Laplace pressure, which is proportional to the mean curvature of the droplet, and is non zero.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This equation relates the contact angle $\theta$ , a geometric property of a sessile droplet to the bulk thermodynamics, the energy at the three phase contact boundary, and the curvature of the surface α.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The first two terms are the modified Young's equation, while the third term is due to the Laplace pressure.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This nonlinear equation correctly predicts the sign and magnitude of κ, the flattening of the contact angle at very small scales, and contact angle hysteresis.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] For many surface/adsorbate configurations, surface energy data and experimental observations are unavailable.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] As wetting interactions are of great importance in various applications, it is often desired to predict and compare the wetting behavior of various material surfaces with particular crystallographic orientations, with relation to water or other adsorbates.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This can be done from an atomistic perspective with tools including molecular dynamics and density functional theory.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In the theoretical prediction of wetting by *ab initio* approaches such as DFT, ice is commonly substituted for water.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This is because DFT calculations are generally conducted assuming conditions of zero thermal movement of atoms, essentially meaning the simulation is conducted at absolute zero.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This simplification nevertheless yields results that are relevant for the adsorption of water under realistic conditions and the use of ice for the theoretical simulation of wetting is commonplace.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Unlike ideal surfaces, real surfaces do not have perfect smoothness, rigidity, or chemical homogeneity.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When the contact angle is between the advancing and receding cases, the contact line is considered to be pinned and hysteretic behaviour can be observed, namely contact angle hysteresis.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When these values are exceeded, the displacement of the contact line, such as the one in Figure 3, will take place by either expansion or retraction of the droplet.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Figure 6 depicts the advancing and receding contact angles.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The advancing contact angle is the maximum stable angle, whereas the receding contact angle is the minimum stable angle.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Contact angle hysteresis occurs because many different thermodynamically stable contact angles are found on a nonideal solid.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] These varying thermodynamically stable contact angles are known as metastable states.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Such motion of a phase boundary, involving advancing and receding contact angles, is known as dynamic wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The difference between dynamic and static wetting angles is proportional to the capillary number, $Ca$ , When a contact line advances, covering more of the surface with liquid, the contact angle is increased and is generally related to the velocity of the contact line.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] If the velocity of a contact line is increased without bound, the contact angle increases, and as it approaches 180°, the gas phase will become entrained in a thin layer between the liquid and solid.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This is a kinetic nonequilibrium effect which results from the contact line moving at such a high speed that complete wetting cannot occur.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A well-known departure from ideal conditions is when the surface of interest has a rough texture.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The rough texture of a surface can fall into one of two categories: homogeneous or heterogeneous.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A homogeneous wetting regime is where the liquid fills in the grooves of a rough surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A heterogeneous wetting regime, though, is where the surface is a composite of two types of patches.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] An important example of such a composite surface is one composed of patches of both air and solid.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Such surfaces have varied effects on the contact angles of wetting liquids.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Cassie–Baxter and Wenzel are the two main models that attempt to describe the wetting of textured surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] However, these equations only apply when the drop size is sufficiently large compared with the surface roughness scale.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When the droplet size is comparable to that of the underlying pillars, the effect of line tension should be considered.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] where $\theta ^{*}$ is the apparent contact angle which corresponds to the stable equilibrium state (i.e. minimum free energy state for the system).
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The roughness ratio, *r*, is a measure of how surface roughness affects a homogeneous surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The roughness ratio is defined as the ratio of true area of the solid surface to the apparent area.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When dealing with a heterogeneous surface, the Wenzel model is not sufficient.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A more complex model is needed to measure how the apparent contact angle changes when various materials are involved.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Here the *rf* is the roughness ratio of the wet surface area and *f* is the fraction of solid surface area wet by the liquid.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When *f* = 1 and *r**f* = *r*, the Cassie–Baxter equations becomes the Wenzel equation.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] On the other hand, when there are many different fractions of surface roughness, each fraction of the total surface area is denoted by $f_{i}$ .
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A summation of all $f_{i}$ equals 1 or the total surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Here $\gamma$ is the Cassie–Baxter surface tension between liquid and vapor, $\gamma _{i,sv}$ is the solid vapor surface tension of every component, and $\gamma _{i,sl}$ is the solid liquid surface tension of every component.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A case that is worth mentioning is when the liquid drop is placed on the substrate and creates small air pockets underneath it.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Here the key difference to notice is that there is no surface tension between the solid and the vapor for the second surface tension component.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This is because of the assumption that the surface of air that is exposed is under the droplet and is the only other substrate in the system.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Subsequently, the equation is then expressed as (1 – *f*).
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Therefore, the Cassie equation can be easily derived from the Cassie–Baxter equation.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Experimental results regarding the surface properties of Wenzel versus Cassie–Baxter systems showed the effect of pinning for a Young angle of 180 to 90°, a region classified under the Cassie–Baxter model.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This liquid/air composite system is largely hydrophobic.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] After that point, a sharp transition to the Wenzel regime was found where the drop wets the surface, but no further than the edges of the drop.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Actually, the Young, Wenzel and Cassie-Baxter equations represent the transversality conditions of the variational problem of wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] With the advent of high resolution imaging, researchers have started to obtain experimental data which have led them to question the assumptions of the Cassie–Baxter equation when calculating the apparent contact angle.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] These groups believe the apparent contact angle is largely dependent on the triple line.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The triple line, which is in contact with the heterogeneous surface, cannot rest on the heterogeneous surface like the rest of the drop.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In theory, it should follow the surface imperfection.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This bending in the triple line is unfavorable and is not seen in real-world situations.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] A theory that preserves the Cassie–Baxter equation while at the same time explaining the presence of the minimized energy state of the triple line hinges on the idea of a precursor film.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This film of submicrometer thickness advances ahead of the motion of the droplet and is found around the triple line.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Furthermore, this precursor film allows the triple line to bend and take different conformations that were originally considered unfavorable.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This precursor fluid has been observed using environmental scanning electron microscopy (ESEM) in surfaces with pores formed in the bulk.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] With the introduction of the precursor film concept, the triple line can follow energetically feasible conformations, thereby correctly explaining the Cassie–Baxter model.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The intrinsic hydrophobicity of a surface can be enhanced by being textured with different length scales of roughness.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The red rose takes advantage of this by using a hierarchy of micro- and nanostructures on each petal to provide sufficient roughness for superhydrophobicity.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] More specifically, each rose petal has a collection of micropapillae on the surface and each papilla, in turn, has many nanofolds.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The term petal effect describes the fact that a water droplet on the surface of a rose petal is spherical in shape, but cannot roll off even if the petal is turned upside down.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The water drops maintain their spherical shape due to the superhydrophobicity of the petal (contact angle of about 152.4°), but do not roll off because the petal surface has a high adhesive force with water.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When comparing the petal effect to the lotus effect, the surface structure of the lotus leaf and the rose petal, as seen in Figure 9, can be used to explain the two different effects.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The lotus leaf has a randomly rough surface and low contact angle hysteresis, which means the water droplet is not able to wet the microstructure spaces between the spikes.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This allows air to remain inside the texture, causing a heterogeneous surface composed of both air and solid.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] As a result, the adhesive force between the water and the solid surface is extremely low, allowing the water to roll off easily (i.e. self-cleaning phenomenon).
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The rose petal's micro- and nanostructures are larger in scale than those of the lotus leaf, which allows the liquid film to impregnate the texture.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] However, as seen in Figure 9, the liquid can enter the larger-scale grooves, but it cannot enter into the smaller grooves.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This is known as the Cassie impregnating wetting regime.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Since the liquid can wet the larger-scale grooves, the adhesive force between the water and solid is very high.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This explains why the water droplet will not fall off even if the petal is tilted at an angle or turned upside down.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] This effect will fail if the droplet has a volume larger than 10 μL because the balance between weight and surface tension is surpassed.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In the Cassie–Baxter model, the drop sits on top of the textured surface with trapped air underneath.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] During the wetting transition from the Cassie state to the Wenzel state, the air pockets are no longer thermodynamically stable and liquid begins to nucleate from the middle of the drop, creating a "mushroom state" as seen in Figure 10.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The penetration front propagates to minimize the surface energy until it reaches the edges of the drop, thus arriving at the Wenzel state.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Since the solid can be considered an absorptive material due to its surface roughness, this phenomenon of spreading and imbibition is called hemiwicking.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The contact angles at which spreading/imbibition occurs are between 0 and *π*/2.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The Wenzel model is valid between *θ*C and *π*/2.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] If the contact angle is less than *Θ*C, the penetration front spreads beyond the drop and a liquid film forms over the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Figure 11 depicts the transition from the Wenzel state to the surface film state.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The film smooths the surface roughness and the Wenzel model no longer applies.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] By fine-tuning the surface roughness, it is possible to achieve a transition between both superhydrophobic and superhydrophilic regions.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Generally, the rougher the surface, the more hydrophobic it is.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] If a drop is placed on a smooth, horizontal surface, it is generally not in the equilibrium state.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Hence, it spreads until an equilibrium contact radius is reached (partial wetting).
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Many technological processes require control of liquid spreading over solid surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When a drop is placed on a surface, it can completely wet, partially wet, or not wet the surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] By reducing the surface tension with surfactants, a nonwetting material can be made to become partially or completely wetting.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Based on this equation, the excess free energy is minimized when *γ* decreases, *γ*SL decreases, or *γ*SV increases.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Surfactants are absorbed onto the liquid–vapor, solid–liquid, and solid–vapor interfaces, which modify the wetting behavior of hydrophobic materials to reduce the free energy.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] When surfactants are absorbed onto a hydrophobic surface, the polar head groups face into the solution with the tail pointing outward.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In more hydrophobic surfaces, surfactants may form a bilayer on the solid, causing it to become more hydrophilic.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The dynamic drop radius can be characterized as the drop begins to spread.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] As the surfactants are absorbed, the solid–vapor surface tension increases and the edges of the drop become hydrophilic.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Ferrocene is a redox-active organometallic compound which can be incorporated into various monomers and used to make polymers which can be tethered onto a surface.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Vinylferrocene (ferroceneylethene) can be prepared by a Wittig reaction and then polymerized to form polyvinylferrocene (PVFc), an analog of polystyrene.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Another polymer which can be formed is poly(2-(methacryloyloxy)ethyl ferrocenecarboxylate), PFcMA.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Both PVFc and PFcMA have been tethered onto silica wafers and the wettability measured when the polymer chains are uncharged and when the ferrocene moieties are oxidised to produce positively charged groups, as illustrated at right.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The contact angle with water on the PFcMA-coated wafers was 70° smaller following oxidation, while in the case of PVFc the decrease was 30°, and the switching of wettability has been shown to be reversible.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] In the PFcMA case, the effect of longer chains with more ferrocene groups (and also greater molar mass) has been investigated, and it was found that longer chains produce significantly larger contact angle reductions.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Rare earth oxides exhibit intrinsic hydrophobicity, and hence can be used in thermally stable heat exchangers and other applications involving high-temperature hydrophobicity.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The presence of oxygen vacancies at surfaces of ceria or other rare earth oxides is instrumental in governing surface wettability.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] Adsorption of water at oxide surfaces can occur as molecular adsorption, in which H2O molecules remain intact at the terminated surface, or as dissociative adsorption, in which OH and H are adsorbed separately at solid surfaces.
[src:surface-chemistry/wetting] The presence of oxygen vacancies is generally found to enhance hydrophobicity while promoting dissociative adsorption.
